description: From Middle English stinken, from Old English stincan, from Proto-Germanic *stinkwaną, from Proto-Indo-European *stengʷ-, *stegʷ- (“to push, thrust, strike”). Cognate with West Frisian stjonke (“to stink”), Dutch stinken (“to stink”), German stinken (“to stink”), Danish stinke (“to stink”), Swedish stinka (“to stink”), Icelandic stökkva (“to spring, leap, jump”).

adjectives.description: stink (comparative more stink, superlative most stink)

examples: The concert was stink. / That was a stink concert.
Everyone is up in arms but it smells stink because it smells of racism…
If you don't make a stink about the problem, nothing will be done.

verbs.description: stink (third-person singular simple present stinks, present participle stinking, simple past stank or stunk, past participle stunk)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To have a strong bad smell.
(intransitive, stative, informal) To be greatly inferior; to perform badly.
examples: That movie stinks. I didn't even stay for the end.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To give an impression of dishonesty, untruth, or sin.
examples: Something stinks about the politician's excuses.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To cause to stink; to affect by a stink.
